    "extractor": "agent",
    "summary": "Paper reanalyzes 40 B-type stars from the MMT HVS survey. 22 HVS-numbered stars are treated as possibly unbound and included as candidates. 15 B-numbered stars remain bound and are excluded. B576, though initially flagged as possibly unbound under a disfavoured MS assumption, is concluded to be a bound BHB star and excluded.",
    "tooling": null
  },
  "method_chain": [
    {
      "id": "step-01",
      "depends_on": [],
      "step_type": "input_catalog",
      "summary": "Input data: MMT HVS survey flux-calibrated spectra (Warren Brown), Gaia DR2 astrometry and photometry, HST proper motions for 15 stars, and photometric catalogs (GALEX, SDSS, Pan-STARRS1, Gaia, UKIDSS, VISTA, SkyMapper, etc.).",
      "source_refs": [
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "path": "literature/2003.12766/arxiv_source/aa.tex",
          "start_line": 99,
          "end_line": 99,
          "context": "In this work, which we regard as Paper~III in this series, we extend the spectrophotometric analysis to 40 out of the 42 high-velocity outliers of the MMT HVS sample."
        },
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "path": "literature/2003.12766/arxiv_source/aa.tex",
          "start_line": 272,
          "end_line": 272,
          "context": "Photometric data were compiled from a variety of surveys covering the ultraviolet, the optical, and the infrared mainly using the VizieR catalog access tool."
        },
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "path": "literature/2003.12766/arxiv_source/aa.tex",
          "start_line": 288,
          "end_line": 288,
          "context": "Proper motions were mainly taken from Gaia DR2. ... For a subsample of 15 stars, pre-Gaia proper motions measured with the HST instruments WFC3 and ACS were available."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "step-02",
      "depends_on": ["step-01"],
      "step_type": "cross_match",
      "summary": "Cross-match of MMT target list with Gaia DR2 and HST catalogs; when both Gaia and HST proper motions are available, the more precise measurement is selected (HST for HVS1, HVS10, HVS12, HVS13; Gaia for B711).",
      "source_refs": [
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "path": "literature/2003.12766/arxiv_source/aa.tex",
          "start_line": 288,
          "end_line": 288,
          "context": "Proper motions were mainly taken from Gaia DR2. ... For a subsample of 15 stars, pre-Gaia proper motions measured with the HST ... we chose the more precise measurement when Gaia as well as HST proper motions were available."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "step-03",
      "depends_on": ["step-01"],
      "step_type": "stellar_parameter_inference",
      "summary": "Spectroscopic analysis: simultaneous fit of all available MMT flux-calibrated spectra using χ² minimization to derive effective temperature T_eff, surface gravity log(g), and projected rotational velocity v sin(i). Additional parameters: interstellar reddening E(B−V), distance scaling factor, with R_V fixed at 3.1, using non-LTE model spectra (ADS approach).",
      "source_refs": [
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "path": "literature/2003.12766/arxiv_source/aa.tex",
          "start_line": 132,
          "end_line": 150,
          "context": "The basic strategy of the spectral analysis is very similar to Paper I. ... The spectral analysis strategy basically followed Irrgang et al. (2014). ... We were thus left with four fitting parameters for the stellar spectrum: the effective temperature T_eff, the surface gravity log(g), the projected rotational velocity v sin(i), and the radial velocity v_rad."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "step-03b",
      "depends_on": ["step-01"],
      "step_type": "radial_velocity_measurement",
      "summary": "Radial velocities v_rad measured from fitting flux-calibrated MMT spectra via χ² minimization.",
      "source_refs": [
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "path": "literature/2003.12766/arxiv_source/aa.tex",
          "start_line": 144,
          "end_line": 144,
          "context": "The spectral analysis strategy ... We were thus left with four fitting parameters: ... the radial velocity v_rad."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "step-04",
      "depends_on": ["step-01", "step-03"],
      "step_type": "photometric_or_sed_modeling",
      "summary": "SED fitting: Observed spectral energy distributions (SEDs) are constructed from compiled photometry and compared to synthetic SEDs based on Atlas12 models with parameters fixed to spectroscopic values. Only angular diameter Θ and color excess E(B−V) are fitted to derive Θ and reddening.",
      "source_refs": [
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "path": "literature/2003.12766/arxiv_source/aa.tex",
          "start_line": 276,
          "end_line": 276,
          "context": "The resulting observed SEDs were compared to synthetic ones based on Atlas12 model computations ... we were left with only two free fitting parameters, the angular diameter Θ as distance scaling factor and the color excess E(B−V) as indicator for interstellar reddening and extinction."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "step-05",
      "depends_on": ["step-03", "step-04"],
      "step_type": "distance_estimation",
      "summary": "Spectrophotometric distances: combine angular diameters Θ = 2 R / d with stellar radii R = (G M / g)^{1/2} derived from spectroscopic surface gravity and masses from evolutionary tracks (rotating MS models).",
      "source_refs": [
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "path": "literature/2003.12766/arxiv_source/aa.tex",
          "start_line": 280,
          "end_line": 281,
          "context": "The resulting angular diameters Θ = 2 R/d were combined with the stellar radii R = (G M/g)^{1/2} which are based on the surface gravities g from spectroscopy and the stellar masses derived from evolutionary tracks ... This allowed us to calculate the spectrophotometric distances d which are listed in Table 3."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "step-06",
      "depends_on": ["step-02"],
      "step_type": "quality_filter",
      "summary": "Astrometric quality filter: the renormalised unit weight error (RUWE) from Gaia DR2 is used as the primary quality indicator. All objects have RUWE < 1.4, indicating well-behaved astrometric solutions. The more precise proper motion (Gaia or HST) is chosen when both are available.",
      "source_refs": [
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "path": "literature/2003.12766/arxiv_source/aa.tex",
          "start_line": 288,
          "end_line": 288,
          "context": "We used the 'renormalized unit weight error' (RUWE) ... as primary indicator for the quality of the astrometric solution. ... For all objects in the sample, RUWE is below the recommended value of 1.4, indicating that the astrometric solutions are well-behaved."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "step-07",
      "depends_on": [],
      "step_type": "solar_position_and_motion",
      "summary": "Solar position and motion parameters are not explicitly stated in this paper; they are presumably from Paper II (2018A&A...620A..48I).",
      "parameters": []
    },
    {
      "id": "step-08",
      "depends_on": ["step-02", "step-03", "step-03b", "step-05", "step-06", "step-07"],
      "step_type": "velocity_calculation",
      "summary": "Transformation to a right-handed Cartesian Galactic coordinate system (Sun on negative x-axis, z-axis to north). Compute Galactocentric positions (x,y,z) and velocities (v_x,v_y,v_z), Galactic rest-frame velocity v_Grf, and ejection velocities (v_Grf at plane crossing corrected for Galactic rotation).",
      "source_refs": [
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "path": "literature/2003.12766/arxiv_source/aa.tex",
          "start_line": 307,
          "end_line": 307,
          "context": "The quantities shown there are based on a right-handed Cartesian Galactic coordinate system in which the Sun is located on the negative x-axis and the z-axis points to the Galactic north pole."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "step-09",
      "depends_on": [],
      "step_type": "galactic_potential_model",
      "summary": "Two Galactic mass models: Model I, a revision of the Allen & Santillan (1991) model; Model II, based on the flat rotation curve model of Wilkinson & Evans (1999). Both models are calibrated using the same observational constraints and are consistent with Gaia DR2 results.",
      "parameters": [
        {
          "name": "potential_name",
          "raw_value": "Model I (revised Allen & Santillan 1991)",
          "value": "Model I",
          "source_refs": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "path": "literature/2003.12766/arxiv_source/aa.tex",
              "start_line": 293,
              "end_line": 293,
              "context": "Model I is a revision of the popular model by Allen & Santillan (1991) and Model II is based on the flat rotation curve model by Wilkinson & Evans (1999)."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "name": "potential_name",
          "raw_value": "Model II (flat rotation curve, Wilkinson & Evans 1999)",
          "value": "Model II",
          "source_refs": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "path": "literature/2003.12766/arxiv_source/aa.tex",
              "start_line": 293,
              "end_line": 293,
              "context": "Model II is based on the flat rotation curve model by Wilkinson & Evans (1999)."
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "step-10",
      "depends_on": ["step-08", "step-09", "step-07", "step-03"],
      "step_type": "orbit_integration",
      "summary": "Orbit integration: Monte Carlo backward integration (1.5 million trials) of trajectories for up to 15 Gyr, using current phase-space information and accounting for uncertainties in distance, radial velocity, and proper motions. Only orbits that cross the Galactic plane within the upper 99% confidence limit of the stellar age are considered for origin determination.",
      "source_refs": [
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "path": "literature/2003.12766/arxiv_source/aa.tex",
          "start_line": 284,
          "end_line": 284,
          "context": "The strategy of the kinematic analysis is identical to that of Paper II. Complementing our revised radial velocities and spectrophotometric distances with positions and proper motions ... gave us the full six-dimensional phase space information that is needed to calculate the trajectories of the program stars back in time to unravel their (spatial) origin. Propagation of uncertainties ... was achieved using a standard Monte Carlo approach with 1.5 million realizations."
        },
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "path": "literature/2003.12766/arxiv_source/aa.tex",
          "start_line": 297,
          "end_line": 298,
          "context": "Tracing back the trajectories of the targets also gave us information about their spatial origin within the Galactic plane. To this end, we considered only those out of the 1.5 million Monte Carlo orbits that cross the Galactic plane within the upper 99% confidence limit for the respective stellar age."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "step-11",
      "depends_on": ["step-08", "step-09", "step-10"],
      "step_type": "escape_or_bound_assessment",
      "summary": "Bound/unbound assessment: Compute local escape velocity v_esc from the Galactic potential, the escape velocity excess (v_Grf − v_esc), and the bound probability P_b (percentage) from the Monte Carlo orbits.",
      "source_refs": [
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "path": "literature/2003.12766/arxiv_source/aa.tex",
          "start_line": 307,
          "end_line": 307,
          "context": "The Galactic rest-frame velocity v_Grf, the local Galactic escape velocity v_esc, (...), the ejection velocity v_ej, and the flight time τ_flight are listed in addition to Cartesian positions and velocities."
        },
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "path": "literature/2003.12766/arxiv_source/aa.tex",
          "start_line": 440,
          "end_line": 442,
          "context": "Whether a star is bound to the Galaxy or not is determined by the Galactic potential, in particular the mass of the Galactic dark matter halo. ... The (analytic) representations for the different Galactic components that we use are consistent with various Gaia DR2 based studies."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "step-12",
      "depends_on": ["step-10", "step-03"],
      "step_type": "origin_assessment",
      "summary": "Origin assessment: classify stars into origin categories (unconstrained, outer rim, disk origin) based on plane-crossing locations of Monte Carlo orbits; compare flight times to evolutionary ages; determine ejection velocities at plane crossing.",
      "source_refs": [
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "path": "literature/2003.12766/arxiv_source/aa.tex",
          "start_line": 322,
          "end_line": 322,
          "context": "In the following, we group the stars in three categories based on their inferred spatial origin."
        },
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "path": "literature/2003.12766/arxiv_source/aa.tex",
          "start_line": 297,
          "end_line": 297,
          "context": "Tracing back the trajectories of the targets also gave us information about their spatial origin within the Galactic plane."
        }
      ]
    }
